    "projects": [
        {
            "title": "A life cycle perspective of water conservation and resource recovery strategies in the urban water system",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 2,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2020
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 12,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2020
                }
            },
            "description": "With the rapid urbanization and growing population, some of the main issues in sustainable management of the water systems in cities include the qualitative and quantitative protection of the natural resources. The transition towards water conservation and resource recovery via the waste(water) streams is a major challenge nowadays. To meet the high demands of urban life, resources need to be efficiently used and resource recovery from generated \u201cwaste\u201d streams should become a \u201cnew normal\u201d. Water and wastewater can provide an alternative and environmentally viable source of resources supporting the resilience of natural systems under water stress. There are many resources that can be recovered via the water path, such as water itself, energy and components such as nutrients and metals.\n\nHowever, circular solutions do not necessarily equate to sustainable solutions! The urban water system is a complex of interconnected processes which should be explored, one by one, in order to create an overall sustainable value. The case study of the research was Prinseneiland neighborhood and the wider area of Amsterdam, the Netherlands. Eight scenarios were assessed in total and the environmental impacts were quantified in terms of life cycle energy consumption, life cycle global warming potential, life cycle water consumption and life cycle freshwater eutrophication potential. The first set of four scenarios involved household-level interventions only: greywater treatment and reuse, rainwater harvesting and use, usage of water efficient appliances, and food waste valorisation via wastewater streams. The second set of four scenarios added centralised phosphorus and nitrogen recovery. All the involved water, energy and nutrient fluxes, as well as byproducts and recovered materials in the urban water system were collected, calculated, assessed and interpreted. Life cycle assessment (LCA) was the methodology used to assess the environmental impacts of the scenarios under study. \n\n\n",
            "contributors": [
                {
                    "type": "standardizedContributor",
                    "first_name": "Elisavet",
                    "last_name": "Apostolidou",
                    "name": null,
                    "headline": "Engineering Project Management"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "title": "High-resolution drone imagery for improving the accuracy of flood models",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 4,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2019
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 6,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2019
                }
            },
            "description": "Increasing impacts of recent floods have raised the awareness and practice of building flood models\nand forecasting systems. However, the availability of suitable data limits the accuracy of flood\nmodels. This paper compares a flood model for a reservoir in the Waark catchment in Luxembourg\nbefore and after adding digital surface model (DSM) cross-sections, obtained by drone imagery,\nto the available digital elevation model (DEM) of Luxembourg. The comparison shows that by\nadding such a DSM, a more accurate flood model can be obtained.",
