        {
            "title": "Legal framework of water reuse in Greece and other European countries",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 11,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2018
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 1,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2019
                }
            },
            "description": "In the last decades the issue of water reuse has arisen. The EU legislation for water reuse is analysed, as well as the regimes of several MS\u2019 and their compliance with the EU Environmental Legislation. The subject of this paper is mainly the water reuse topic and the main focus is the case of Greece. The country\u2019s framework for reclamation and reuse of water is presented, with references to the national Common Ministerial Decisions (CMDs) that have been introduced. Based on the research we can conclude that the most important weakness, until recently, in the EU in what so ever concerns the regulation of the issue of the reclamation and water reuse is the lack of EU guidelines and the harmony between the guidelines developed by the MS. The introduction of an EU instrument in the form of Regulation is essential and urgent in Europe, obliging all the MS to develop similar regimes and adopt the same criteria, techniques and methods in order to proceed with water reuse and exchange knowledge relatively. For the case of Greece, this is a big challenge and the country will struggle to harmonize its legislation with a new EU instrument, while its previous obligations are still pending.  ",
            "contributors": [
                {
                    "type": "standardizedContributor",
                    "first_name": "Elisavet",
                    "last_name": "Apostolidou",
                    "name": null,
                    "headline": "Engineering Project Management"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "title": "Application of grey water reuse in small-scale hotels",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 10,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2017
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 6,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2018
                }
            },
            "description": "This research is a MSc Thesis in Aristotle University of Thessaloniki. The project focuses on the assessment of grey water reuse in touristic regions, as an approach to solve the intense water scarcity that all the islands and coastal regions of Greece are facing every summer. Through the innovative, for Greece, proposal for the reuse of grey water, the reduction of clean potable water use for secondary uses and the introduction of grey water reuse in toilet flushing and irrigation of gardens, will help overcome this huge problem in touristic areas. In this thesis, the pilot application of grey water reuse in a small-scale hotel located in the area of Pefkohori, Chalkidiki is studied. This area faces serious water shortages during the summer months, due to intense touristic activity, and is in a risk of depleting its water reserves and entering brackish water into the aquifer. \n\nA thorough literature review has been performed in terms of the grey water characteristics, its main applications and advantages. It was also conducted research on the several grey water reuse units that are available in the market. The thesis focused on a specific hotel, where, after a detailed analysis of the topography and the existing construction (creation of the architectural plans, inventory of the building materials used), an economical and technical analysis of new sewerage, water supply and irrigation networks was conducted. This study was completed with the calculation of the cost of the construction of the new networks and the various facilities required, as well as the purchase of the wastewater treatment unit. The goal of this dissertation was to determine whether this implementation is environmentally sustainable and economically beneficial for the owners of the hotel. \n\nThe architectural plans of the hotel were designed using AutoCAD and ArchiCAD.\n",
